        F=open(filedoc,'r')
        t=F.read()
        F.close()
        # ... and maping its content
        doc=json.loads(t)
        
        # getting just what we need
        # in some docs, abstract comes in several parts
        abstract='\n'.join([part[text] for part in doc['abstract']])
        title=doc['metadata']['title']
        text='\n'.join([s['text'] for s in doc['body_text']])
        # taking as ID of every doc the SHA part of filename
        docID=filedoc.split('/')[-1].replace('.json','')
        
        # saving in outpath, with SHA as file name
        F=open(outpath+'/'+docID,'w')
        F.write(title+'\n'+abstract+'\n'+text)
        F.close()

# first we load modules ans stuff
from gensim.parsing.preprocessing import preprocess_string
from gensim import corpora, models, similarities
from glob import glob

# loading and pre-processing words, with the help of gensim library
pathin='fulltext' # the folder where full plain text of document are
num_topics=50 # we want just 50 topics
ID=[] # we'll keep here IDs of every doc
df=[] # a list of doc's text
for fname in glob(pathin+'/*'):
    F=open(fname,'r')
    t=F.read()
    F.close()
    ID.append(fname.split('/')[-1])
    df.append(preprocess_string(t))
# gensim stuff
dictionary=corpora.Dictionary(df)
corpus=[dictionary.doc2bow(text) for text in df]
tfidf=models.TfidfModel(corpus)
transformed_tfidf=tfidf[corpus]

# calling Mallet
mallet_path='/opt/mallet-2.0.7/bin/mallet' # where Mallet lives (in our installation, btw)
lda = models.wrappers.LdaMallet(mallet_path, corpus=transformed_tfidf, num_topics=num_topics, id2word=dictionary)

# done, lda have the trained model

# importing Similarity class from gensim 
# and computing a kind of matrix os similarities
# (parameter 'temp' is just in case of we don't have 
# enough memory, it swaps to temporary files)
from gensim.similarities import Similarity
index=Similarity('tmp', transformed_tfidf, num_features=len(dictionary))

# now, getting the docs per top-topic
# this is a bit  complicated, because gensim don't have a method
# to get directly docs per topic

# preparing a list of list
# each member of the main list represents a topic and is,
# in his turn another list with the docs for such a topic
topics=[]
for e in range(0,50):
    topics.append([])

# now, getting the topics an their probabilities for
# every doc. 
# topic with max prob is the top-topic for this topic
for e in range(len(corpus)):
    x=max(lda.get_document_topics(corpus[e]),key=lambda z:z[1])[0]
    topics[x].append(e)

for t in range(0, len(topics)):
    # keep in a single file one network per topic
    # ncol is a suitable format for networks, 
    # easily readable for most of software
    F=open('topic'+str(t)+'.ncol',w)

        for k in range(j+1, len(doc)):
            s=index.similarity_by_id(j)[k]
            F.write(str(j)+' '+str(k)+' '+str(s)+'\n')
    F.close()

# Function model definition
model <- function(file) {
  # Read graph file and convert it into a netCoin object
  G.igraph  <- read_graph(file, format="ncol")
  G.netCoin <- fromIgraph(G.igraph)
  # Edition of title and labels
  N <- as.numeric(sub("^.*(\\d{2}).*","\\1", file))
  Ti <- paste0(gsub("(Red)(\\d+).ncol", "Topic \\2", file), " (",
               words$words5[[N]],", ...)")
  G.netCoin$nodes$paper <- iconv(G.netCoin$nodes$paper, from="UTF-8")
  # Modification of the G.netcoin object
  netCoin(G.netCoin, label="paper", community = "walktrap", color="community",
          size="degree", labelSize="degree", lwidth= "weight", lweight="",
          degreeFilter = 1, linkFilter = "weight>.7",
          cex=1.4, repulsion=7, zoom=0.66, controls=c(2,4,5),
          main=Ti, note="Graph example")
}

## R netCoin 

The aim of the netCoin R package is to explore data structures using a number of statistical techniques that share the treatment of interdependent variables. Its main objective is to detect events, characters, objects, attributes or characteristics that tend to appear together within a given set of scenarios. Its most notable feature is the combination of traditional multivariate statistical analysis and network analysis supported by topological graph theory. 
Among its many applications, netCoin can be used for the analysis of multiple responses in questionnaires to explore relevant associations, for the development of textual networks, for audience analysis, for mining large databases or for basket market analysis.

Data consists on academic papers on coronavid-19 and related research. For every paper we have metadata (authors, journal, date, title and so on...), as well as full text (including Annexes, Appendices, References, etc.)
Data comes in several folders, one single JSON file per paper; also, we got a CSV file with metadata foral papers.
Each paper JSON file have as filename a SHA key; this will be the ID of every paper.

We start by cleaning papers of unwanted data and joining them in a single directory.
source.d00380c9:
## Introduction

Once data are organized, two types of networks are built. The first one consists of a single network with an index function, which is formed by the links between each topic and the terms or words that characterize it.  The second is made up of as many networks as there are topics. In each of them, a node represents an article and the link reflects the number of common words through the tf-idf indicator. In this first part, we explain how the index network can be generated and in the second part we will show the generation of the thematic networks.

### Computing doc's networks

This is a bit complicated; first, for a given topic, we'll collect all docs which have as top-topic such topic; then, with those docs we'll make a network in which the nodes are those docs, and the links are the semantic simmilarity between each pair of docs.

*Semantic simmilarity* is computed  following a *TF*x*IDF* schema. Gensim has tools to do it
